    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''For Muslim Americans, Influence in Politics Still Hard to Come By'' (front page, Oct. 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''For Muslim Americans, Influence in Politics Still Hard to Come By'' (front page, Oct. 27):</p>
        <p>The decision by Hillary Rodham Clinton to return campaign contributions by American Muslim organizations is a slap in the face of this country's fastest growing religious-cultural community, and it raises disturbing questions of how some segments of our diverse population are considered more equal than others.</p>
        <p>American Jewish organizations have never been expected to condemn Israeli atrocities or to curtail financing of extremist Jewish settler movements in the occupied Palestinian territories. The American Muslim community will fight for and achieve recognition in our still circumscribed democracy, like our African-American, Hispanic and Asian-American compatriots before us.</p>
        <p>MUJEEB R. KHAN  Policy Coordinator  Muslim Voters of America  Oak Park, Ill., Oct. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
